helps to bring that object to

00:25:16.536 --> 00:25:18.386 A:middle
life with an idle animation that

00:25:18.386 --> 00:25:19.506 A:middle
makes it feel more like it's in

00:25:19.506 --> 00:25:19.906 A:middle
the world.

00:25:20.426 --> 00:25:23.266 A:middle
Note that animations always

00:25:23.266 --> 00:25:25.556 A:middle
loop, and the animations you

00:25:25.556 --> 00:25:26.936 A:middle
could create can use skeletal

00:25:27.106 --> 00:25:28.876 A:middle
and/or transform animation to

00:25:28.876 --> 00:25:30.906 A:middle
bring them to life.

00:25:31.046 --> 00:25:32.136 A:middle
Here's another example.

00:25:32.586 --> 00:25:34.166 A:middle
This is a cartoon style chicken

00:25:34.166 --> 00:25:36.406 A:middle
character without animation, and

00:25:36.506 --> 00:25:38.276 A:middle
if I place him in the world, he

00:25:38.276 --> 00:25:40.276 A:middle
looks pretty cool, but he's kind

00:25:40.406 --> 00:25:40.756 A:middle
of static.

00:25:40.756 --> 00:25:42.146 A:middle
He doesn't really feel like he's

00:25:42.146 --> 00:25:43.446 A:middle
alive there in the room with me.

00:25:44.216 --> 00:25:45.926 A:middle
So, there's more we can do here.

00:25:46.676 --> 00:25:48.426 A:middle
So, if we add a little bit of

00:25:48.426 --> 00:25:49.686 A:middle
skeletal animation to our

00:25:49.686 --> 00:25:50.956 A:middle
character to make him bob his

00:25:51.026 --> 00:25:53.376 A:middle
head, now when we place him in

00:25:53.376 --> 00:25:55.036 A:middle
the world, he feels much more

00:25:55.036 --> 00:25:56.286 A:middle
realistic, much more like he's

00:25:56.286 --> 00:25:58.106 A:middle
there on the table in front of

00:25:59.656 --> 00:25:59.736 A:middle
me.

00:25:59.986 --> 00:26:01.716 A:middle
Some tips as you add animation


00:25:59.986 --> 00:26:01.716 A:middle
Some tips as you add animation

00:26:01.716 --> 00:26:02.306 A:middle
to your models.

00:26:03.026 --> 00:26:04.986 A:middle
Firstly, choose animations that

00:26:04.986 --> 00:26:06.796 A:middle
enhance the AR immersiveness,

00:26:06.856 --> 00:26:07.946 A:middle
that make you feel more like

00:26:07.946 --> 00:26:08.876 A:middle
that object is there in the

00:26:08.876 --> 00:26:08.976 A:middle
room.

00:26:10.396 --> 00:26:11.826 A:middle
Now, because people can

00:26:11.826 --> 00:26:13.306 A:middle
manipulate your objects, they

00:26:13.306 --> 00:26:14.996 A:middle
can retape them, scale them, and

00:26:14.996 --> 00:26:17.206 A:middle
move them around, it's important

00:26:17.206 --> 00:26:18.296 A:middle
not to move them away from the

00:26:18.296 --> 00:26:18.696 A:middle
origin.

00:26:19.586 --> 00:26:21.306 A:middle
If I create a car that zooms

00:26:21.306 --> 00:26:22.806 A:middle
around in a meter-wide circle,

00:26:23.486 --> 00:26:24.386 A:middle
when someone tries to put their

00:26:24.386 --> 00:26:25.566 A:middle
finger on that car to pick it

00:26:25.566 --> 00:26:27.176 A:middle
up, it's already moved away and

00:26:27.176 --> 00:26:28.026 A:middle
zooms somewhere else.

00:26:28.336 --> 00:26:29.256 A:middle
So, that gesture is very

00:26:29.256 --> 00:26:30.576 A:middle
confusing to somebody trying to

00:26:30.576 --> 00:26:31.496 A:middle
manipulate that object.

00:26:32.106 --> 00:26:33.306 A:middle
So, try and keep those objects

00:26:33.306 --> 00:26:34.156 A:middle
centered at the origin.

00:26:34.686 --> 00:26:37.536 A:middle
For the same reasons, try and

00:26:37.536 --> 00:26:39.176 A:middle
keep a consistent bounding box

00:26:39.176 --> 00:26:40.096 A:middle
throughout the animation as

00:26:40.096 --> 00:26:40.316 A:middle
well.

00:26:40.856 --> 00:26:42.016 A:middle
Even if the object is at one

00:26:42.016 --> 00:26:44.036 A:middle
location, it's much easier for

00:26:44.036 --> 00:26:45.606 A:middle
me to manipulate it if it stays

00:26:45.606 --> 00:26:46.496 A:middle
in the same place under my

00:26:46.496 --> 00:26:48.116 A:middle
fingers throughout the entire

00:26:48.116 --> 00:26:48.496 A:middle
gesture.

00:26:50.586 --> 00:26:53.016 A:middle
As a result, prefer animations

00:26:53.016 --> 00:26:54.446 A:middle
that make sense at a static

00:26:54.446 --> 00:26:54.936 A:middle
location.

00:26:55.916 --> 00:26:57.516 A:middle
If you have a T-rex character,

00:26:57.516 --> 00:26:59.256 A:middle
rather than giving it a walk

00:26:59.256 --> 00:27:00.656 A:middle
cycle that would make it look


00:26:59.256 --> 00:27:00.656 A:middle
cycle that would make it look

00:27:00.656 --> 00:27:01.706 A:middle
like it was running on the spot,

00:27:02.336 --> 00:27:03.946 A:middle
make it roar or stamp its feet

00:27:04.406 --> 00:27:05.316 A:middle
or something else that makes

00:27:05.316 --> 00:27:06.526 A:middle
sense at a static location.

00:27:07.106 --> 00:27:09.396 A:middle
Now, there is an alternative.

00:27:10.076 --> 00:27:11.826 A:middle
You can also consider creating

00:27:11.826 --> 00:27:13.216 A:middle
animations as self-contained

00:27:13.216 --> 00:27:14.636 A:middle
scenes to help with these

00:27:14.636 --> 00:27:15.636 A:middle
gesture manipulations.

00:27:16.046 --> 00:27:17.256 A:middle
And let's see an example of how

00:27:17.256 --> 00:27:17.756 A:middle
that can work.

00:27:18.806 --> 00:27:20.566 A:middle
Here, I have a swimming koi

00:27:20.566 --> 00:27:22.236 A:middle
fish, and it makes sense for

00:27:22.236 --> 00:27:23.176 A:middle
this fish to have some

00:27:23.176 --> 00:27:23.786 A:middle
translation.

00:27:24.406 --> 00:27:25.806 A:middle
So, we created a scene with an

00:27:25.806 --> 00:27:28.106 A:middle
aquarium base, and this means

00:27:28.106 --> 00:27:29.336 A:middle
when we place this in the world,

00:27:29.846 --> 00:27:31.986 A:middle
if we rotate it, or if we move

00:27:31.986 --> 00:27:34.256 A:middle
it, the scene we're manipulating

00:27:34.256 --> 00:27:36.566 A:middle
is the scene, not the fish, and

00:27:36.566 --> 00:27:37.916 A:middle
so the gesture makes a lot more

00:27:37.916 --> 00:27:38.176 A:middle
sense.

00:27:39.476 --> 00:27:40.916 A:middle
It also means by having a base

00:27:40.916 --> 00:27:42.156 A:middle
to our scene that we have a

00:27:42.156 --> 00:27:43.486 A:middle
consistent bounding box

00:27:43.636 --> 00:27:44.876 A:middle
throughout the entire animation.

00:27:45.326 --> 00:27:48.846 A:middle
Another thing that really brings

00:27:48.846 --> 00:27:49.996 A:middle
your models to life in the world

00:27:50.376 --> 00:27:51.576 A:middle
is that contact shadow.

00:27:52.466 --> 00:27:54.496 A:middle
Now, note here that AR Quick

00:27:54.496 --> 00:27:55.886 A:middle
Look provides the contact shadow

00:27:55.886 --> 00:27:56.386 A:middle
for you.

00:27:57.276 --> 00:27:58.536 A:middle
This means that it can turn the

00:27:58.536 --> 00:27:59.976 A:middle
shadow on and off as you

00:27:59.976 --> 00:28:00.976 A:middle
transition between modes.


00:27:59.976 --> 00:28:00.976 A:middle
transition between modes.

00:28:01.776 --> 00:28:03.196 A:middle
It also means it can apply

00:28:03.416 --> 00:28:05.116 A:middle
ambient lighting conditions to

00:28:05.116 --> 00:28:06.836 A:middle
the shadow as the lighting

00:28:06.836 --> 00:28:07.616 A:middle
changes around you.

00:28:08.816 --> 00:28:10.606 A:middle
Because of this, don't bake a

00:28:10.606 --> 00:28:12.166 A:middle
contact shadow into the models

00:28:12.166 --> 00:28:12.676 A:middle
you provide.

00:28:13.426 --> 00:28:14.626 A:middle
If you do, you'll end up with

00:28:14.626 --> 00:28:14.976 A:middle
two shadows.

00:28:17.436 --> 00:28:19.196 A:middle
Note also that the first frame

00:28:19.196 --> 00:28:20.846 A:middle
of any animation is used to

00:28:20.846 --> 00:28:22.326 A:middle
create the shadow for a model,

00:28:22.996 --> 00:28:24.596 A:middle
and sometimes this means it's

00:28:24.596 --> 00:28:25.626 A:middle
important to choose the right

00:28:25.626 --> 00:28:26.176 A:middle
first frame.

00:28:26.686 --> 00:28:29.206 A:middle
We'll see an example.

00:28:29.206 --> 00:28:30.556 A:middle
Here, I have a model of a

00:28:30.556 --> 00:28:32.536 A:middle
Newton's cradle, a desktop type,

00:28:33.096 --> 00:28:34.476 A:middle
and it has a swinging animation,

00:28:34.476 --> 00:28:35.716 A:middle
a transform animation to bring

00:28:35.716 --> 00:28:36.256 A:middle
it to life.

00:28:36.356 --> 00:28:39.356 A:middle
Now, if we freeze this with its

00:28:39.356 --> 00:28:41.176 A:middle
first frame, here the first

00:28:41.176 --> 00:28:42.046 A:middle
frame has one of the ball

00:28:42.046 --> 00:28:43.796 A:middle
bearings out to the side, we can

00:28:43.796 --> 00:28:44.586 A:middle
see there's a problem.

00:28:45.716 --> 00:28:47.106 A:middle
The shadow we've generated from

00:28:47.106 --> 00:28:48.716 A:middle
this first frame also has that

00:28:48.746 --> 00:28:49.986 A:middle
ball bearing out to the side.

00:28:50.966 --> 00:28:52.546 A:middle
And so, if we animate to the

00:28:52.546 --> 00:28:54.076 A:middle
other extreme of this animation,

00:28:54.696 --> 00:28:55.606 A:middle
at this point, the shadow

00:28:55.606 --> 00:28:58.486 A:middle
doesn't really make sense.

00:28:58.656 --> 00:29:00.686 A:middle
Now, because animations loop, we


00:28:58.656 --> 00:29:00.686 A:middle
Now, because animations loop, we

00:29:00.686 --> 00:29:01.606 A:middle
could choose a different

00:29:01.606 --> 00:29:02.936 A:middle
starting point, a more neutral

00:29:02.936 --> 00:29:03.966 A:middle
one where the ball's in the

00:29:03.966 --> 00:29:06.016 A:middle
center and still have the same

00:29:06.016 --> 00:29:07.166 A:middle
animation, the same overall

00:29:07.166 --> 00:29:07.496 A:middle
effect.

00:29:08.206 --> 00:29:09.676 A:middle
But now, by choosing a better

00:29:09.676 --> 00:29:11.386 A:middle
first frame, our shadow makes

00:29:11.386 --> 00:29:12.306 A:middle
sense throughout the entire

00:29:12.306 --> 00:29:12.756 A:middle
animation.

00:29:15.656 --> 00:29:17.136 A:middle
One of the biggest things we can

00:29:17.136 --> 00:29:18.866 A:middle
modify about our model to make

00:29:18.866 --> 00:29:20.786 A:middle
it feel real in the world is the

00:29:20.786 --> 00:29:21.806 A:middle
model's appearance.

00:29:23.056 --> 00:29:25.486 A:middle
Now, here, AR Quick Look uses a

00:29:25.486 --> 00:29:27.076 A:middle
Physically Based Rendering, or

00:29:27.076 --> 00:29:29.206 A:middle
PBR shader, and this gives us

00:29:29.206 --> 00:29:30.706 A:middle
six things that we can modify

00:29:30.816 --> 00:29:32.406 A:middle
about our model's appearance to

00:29:32.406 --> 00:29:33.836 A:middle
make it feel more real in the

00:29:33.836 --> 00:29:34.146 A:middle
world.

00:29:35.096 --> 00:29:36.206 A:middle
We do this by providing

00:29:36.206 --> 00:29:37.666 A:middle
textures, images, for each of

00:29:37.666 --> 00:29:38.866 A:middle
these six things if we want to.

00:29:40.266 --> 00:29:41.996 A:middle
The first is the model's albedo.

00:29:42.476 --> 00:29:43.916 A:middle
This is the base color of the

00:29:43.916 --> 00:29:45.816 A:middle
model, its underlying color.

00:29:46.456 --> 00:29:48.486 A:middle
The second is indicating which

00:29:48.526 --> 00:29:50.076 A:middle
parts of the model are metallic.

00:29:50.706 --> 00:29:52.076 A:middle
This changes whether they are a

00:29:52.076 --> 00:29:53.836 A:middle
conductor or an insulator, which

00:29:53.836 --> 00:29:55.126 A:middle
changes how they interact with

00:29:55.126 --> 00:29:56.236 A:middle
the physics of light in the real

00:29:56.236 --> 00:29:56.596 A:middle
world.

00:29:58.026 --> 00:29:59.796 A:middle
We could also specify which

00:29:59.846 --> 00:30:01.416 A:middle
parts of our model are rough or


00:29:59.846 --> 00:30:01.416 A:middle
parts of our model are rough or

00:30:01.416 --> 00:30:02.996 A:middle
shiny by providing a roughness

00:30:02.996 --> 00:30:03.366 A:middle
texture.

00:30:04.886 --> 00:30:06.246 A:middle
We can add in a normal map.

00:30:06.896 --> 00:30:08.056 A:middle
This creates the illusion of

00:30:08.116 --> 00:30:09.326 A:middle
depth and variances within the

00:30:09.326 --> 00:30:11.176 A:middle
surfaces, the model's surface,

00:30:11.426 --> 00:30:12.606 A:middle
without changing the underlying

00:30:12.606 --> 00:30:13.026 A:middle
mesh.

00:30:13.596 --> 00:30:16.086 A:middle
We can add an ambient occlusion

00:30:16.086 --> 00:30:17.896 A:middle
texture to specify where the

00:30:17.896 --> 00:30:19.746 A:middle
model casts shadows on itself in

00:30:19.746 --> 00:30:21.036 A:middle
the crevices and nooks and

00:30:21.036 --> 00:30:21.776 A:middle
crannies of the model.

00:30:23.036 --> 00:30:24.726 A:middle
And if our model emits lights,

00:30:25.066 --> 00:30:26.306 A:middle
we can provide an emissive

00:30:26.306 --> 00:30:27.916 A:middle
texture for things like a TV

00:30:27.916 --> 00:30:29.346 A:middle
screen or a computer monitor.

00:30:29.926 --> 00:30:32.276 A:middle
Now, if you're just getting

00:30:32.276 --> 00:30:34.456 A:middle
started with PBR, we have a

00:30:34.456 --> 00:30:35.886 A:middle
session on Thursday about

00:30:35.916 --> 00:30:38.006 A:middle
creating PBR-based models for

00:30:38.006 --> 00:30:39.826 A:middle
any AR experience, and I highly

00:30:39.826 --> 00:30:40.726 A:middle
recommend you check it out.

00:30:42.036 --> 00:30:43.366 A:middle
For now, we'll take a look at

00:30:43.366 --> 00:30:45.306 A:middle
how these six textures affect AR

00:30:45.306 --> 00:30:46.456 A:middle
Quick Look particularly.

00:30:47.996 --> 00:30:49.566 A:middle
So, I'll start with a model of a

00:30:49.566 --> 00:30:50.056 A:middle
TV.

00:30:50.606 --> 00:30:52.106 A:middle
Right now, it has no textures.

00:30:52.196 --> 00:30:53.586 A:middle
It's pretty bland.

00:30:55.016 --> 00:30:57.356 A:middle
We'll bring in an albedo texture

00:30:57.546 --> 00:30:59.386 A:middle
to give it some base color, and

00:30:59.386 --> 00:31:00.746 A:middle
it's much more recognizable as a


00:30:59.386 --> 00:31:00.746 A:middle
it's much more recognizable as a

00:31:00.746 --> 00:31:02.786 A:middle
TV now, but it's still very

00:31:02.786 --> 00:31:03.066 A:middle
flat.

00:31:03.346 --> 00:31:04.426 A:middle
It doesn't feel realistic.

00:31:04.426 --> 00:31:07.976 A:middle
The next thing we'll do is to

00:31:07.976 --> 00:31:10.166 A:middle
introduce a metallic texture to

00:31:10.166 --> 00:31:11.416 A:middle
make the trim around the TV

00:31:11.416 --> 00:31:13.666 A:middle
screen and the antenna on top to

00:31:13.666 --> 00:31:14.776 A:middle
indicate that they're made from

00:31:14.776 --> 00:31:15.086 A:middle
metal.

00:31:16.266 --> 00:31:17.266 A:middle
Note here that our metallic

00:31:17.266 --> 00:31:18.946 A:middle
texture is pretty much black and

00:31:18.946 --> 00:31:19.186 A:middle
white.

00:31:19.676 --> 00:31:21.166 A:middle
Things either are a metal, or

00:31:21.166 --> 00:31:21.436 A:middle
they aren't.

00:31:22.916 --> 00:31:24.206 A:middle
But the metal still doesn't look

00:31:24.206 --> 00:31:25.386 A:middle
as realistic as we want it to

00:31:25.386 --> 00:31:26.886 A:middle
do, and that's because the

00:31:26.886 --> 00:31:28.606 A:middle
metal, like all of the model, is

00:31:28.606 --> 00:31:29.766 A:middle
entirely rough.

00:31:30.056 --> 00:31:31.356 A:middle
There's no shine, there's no

00:31:31.526 --> 00:31:32.916 A:middle
smooth surfaces on this TV right

00:31:32.916 --> 00:31:32.983 A:middle
now.

00:31:35.306 --> 00:31:37.106 A:middle
To fix that, we'll bring in a

00:31:37.106 --> 00:31:39.176 A:middle
roughness texture, and at this

00:31:39.176 --> 00:31:40.316 A:middle
point the model really comes to

00:31:40.316 --> 00:31:40.626 A:middle
life.

00:31:41.656 --> 00:31:43.076 A:middle
The metal around the TV screen

00:31:43.076 --> 00:31:44.506 A:middle
and the aerial now looks like

00:31:44.506 --> 00:31:44.876 A:middle
metal.

00:31:44.876 --> 00:31:46.786 A:middle
It looks like chrome, and the

00:31:46.786 --> 00:31:48.486 A:middle
wood on the top of our TV

00:31:48.616 --> 00:31:49.646 A:middle
actually looks like it has a

00:31:49.646 --> 00:31:51.056 A:middle
varnish or lacquer effect.

00:31:51.236 --> 00:31:52.266 A:middle
We can believe it much more

00:31:52.266 --> 00:31:54.686 A:middle
realistically as a TV.

00:31:54.866 --> 00:31:55.946 A:middle
And roughness is one of the

00:31:55.946 --> 00:31:57.426 A:middle
biggest points of creative

00:31:57.426 --> 00:31:58.696 A:middle
control you have over the look

00:31:58.696 --> 00:31:59.936 A:middle
of your model and how it feels

00:31:59.936 --> 00:32:00.646 A:middle
in the real world.


00:31:59.936 --> 00:32:00.646 A:middle
in the real world.

00:32:01.186 --> 00:32:02.196 A:middle
And you'll see, we have quite a

00:32:02.196 --> 00:32:03.476 A:middle
lot of variance in our roughness

00:32:03.506 --> 00:32:04.726 A:middle
texture, even within the same

00:32:04.726 --> 00:32:06.446 A:middle
parts of the model, to give more

00:32:06.446 --> 00:32:07.516 A:middle
realism and to bring it more to

00:32:07.516 --> 00:32:07.736 A:middle
life.

00:32:10.176 --> 00:32:12.676 A:middle
Next, we'll add a normal map to

00:32:12.676 --> 00:32:14.036 A:middle
add the illusion of variance,

00:32:14.036 --> 00:32:15.866 A:middle
particularly in the woodgrain on

00:32:15.866 --> 00:32:16.846 A:middle
top of the TV here.

00:32:17.426 --> 00:32:18.376 A:middle
The underlying mesh hasn't

00:32:18.376 --> 00:32:20.286 A:middle
changed, but it feels more 3D.

00:32:20.466 --> 00:32:21.616 A:middle
Also, on the speaker grill.

00:32:22.066 --> 00:32:25.506 A:middle
Because we have some crevices

00:32:25.506 --> 00:32:26.686 A:middle
and some hidden areas on the

00:32:26.686 --> 00:32:28.076 A:middle
front of the TV that would cast

00:32:28.076 --> 00:32:29.876 A:middle
shadows on themselves, we'll add

00:32:29.876 --> 00:32:31.516 A:middle
in an ambient occlusion texture.

00:32:31.516 --> 00:32:34.066 A:middle
The effect is pretty subtle, but

00:32:34.066 --> 00:32:35.206 A:middle
it does add to the depth of the

00:32:35.206 --> 00:32:36.906 A:middle
model and make it feel more real

00:32:37.106 --> 00:32:37.796 A:middle
when it's in the world.

00:32:38.366 --> 00:32:41.116 A:middle
And because this is a TV with a

00:32:41.116 --> 00:32:43.176 A:middle
screen, we'll add an emissive

00:32:43.256 --> 00:32:45.056 A:middle
texture as well to indicate that

00:32:45.056 --> 00:32:46.456 A:middle
the screen emits light into the

00:32:46.456 --> 00:32:46.786 A:middle
world.

00:32:48.076 --> 00:32:49.356 A:middle
The effect of this is best seen

00:32:49.356 --> 00:32:50.696 A:middle
when pushing the object into a

00:32:50.696 --> 00:32:51.006 A:middle
room.

00:32:51.786 --> 00:32:53.136 A:middle
Here, we can see that the main

00:32:53.136 --> 00:32:54.706 A:middle
body of the TV reflects the

00:32:54.706 --> 00:32:55.876 A:middle
ambient lighting conditions of

00:32:55.876 --> 00:32:57.466 A:middle
the room it's in, but the screen

00:32:57.466 --> 00:32:58.016 A:middle
is brighter.

00:32:58.016 --> 00:33:00.746 A:middle
It's actually emitting light.


