00:35:04.426 --> 00:35:06.386 A:middle
David mentioned earlier that AR

00:35:06.386 --> 00:35:07.956 A:middle
Quick Look is available on all

00:35:07.956 --> 00:35:10.756 A:middle
devices that support iOS 12, and

00:35:10.756 --> 00:35:12.036 A:middle
this is actually quite a range

00:35:12.036 --> 00:35:13.176 A:middle
of devices with different

00:35:13.176 --> 00:35:13.816 A:middle
capabilities.

00:35:15.306 --> 00:35:17.856 A:middle
Now, because AR Quick Look is a

00:35:17.856 --> 00:35:20.076 A:middle
system-wide extension, this

00:35:20.076 --> 00:35:21.206 A:middle
means it has to share the

00:35:21.206 --> 00:35:22.736 A:middle
available system memory with the

00:35:22.736 --> 00:35:24.026 A:middle
applications that launch it.

00:35:24.026 --> 00:35:26.046 A:middle
And so, there's only so much

00:35:26.046 --> 00:35:27.866 A:middle
memory available to display and

00:35:27.866 --> 00:35:28.626 A:middle
load these models.

00:35:29.306 --> 00:35:32.586 A:middle
To help with this, we recommend

00:35:32.586 --> 00:35:34.366 A:middle
that you create and optimize and

00:35:34.446 --> 00:35:36.376 A:middle
test your models for high memory

00:35:36.376 --> 00:35:38.786 A:middle
devices like the iPhone 7 Plus,

00:35:39.016 --> 00:35:41.706 A:middle
8 Plus, and X, and the iPad Pro

00:35:41.966 --> 00:35:42.816 A:middle
12.9 inch.

00:35:43.916 --> 00:35:45.956 A:middle
If you do this, AR Quick Look

00:35:45.956 --> 00:35:47.736 A:middle
will dynamically downsample the

00:35:47.736 --> 00:35:49.346 A:middle
textures in your model for other

00:35:49.346 --> 00:35:50.206 A:middle
devices of different

00:35:50.206 --> 00:35:51.556 A:middle
capabilities, if needed.

00:35:52.266 --> 00:35:53.216 A:middle
This means you can make the

00:35:53.216 --> 00:35:54.626 A:middle
devices, your models look great

00:35:54.626 --> 00:35:56.076 A:middle
on those devices but still know

00:35:56.076 --> 00:35:56.776 A:middle
they'll work everywhere.

00:35:56.776 --> 00:35:59.786 A:middle
Know that the meshes and the

00:35:59.786 --> 00:36:01.156 A:middle
animations won't be modified.


00:35:59.786 --> 00:36:01.156 A:middle
animations won't be modified.

00:36:01.406 --> 00:36:02.496 A:middle
It's only the textures that will

00:36:02.496 --> 00:36:02.976 A:middle
be downsampled.

00:36:06.276 --> 00:36:07.576 A:middle
You're probably thinking at this

00:36:07.576 --> 00:36:09.506 A:middle
point, okay, so how big can my

00:36:09.506 --> 00:36:09.986 A:middle
model be?

00:36:09.986 --> 00:36:11.706 A:middle
How big and complex can my

00:36:11.706 --> 00:36:12.286 A:middle
textures be?

00:36:12.286 --> 00:36:15.146 A:middle
And the answer is there is no

00:36:15.146 --> 00:36:15.626 A:middle
one answer.

00:36:16.376 --> 00:36:17.986 A:middle
Many factors affect a model's

00:36:17.986 --> 00:36:19.786 A:middle
memory usage, its mesh, and its

00:36:19.786 --> 00:36:21.436 A:middle
animation complexity, and its

00:36:21.436 --> 00:36:22.576 A:middle
textures size and count.

00:36:23.816 --> 00:36:26.536 A:middle
But as a guide, for a model that

00:36:26.536 --> 00:36:28.716 A:middle
has a single PBR texture, using

00:36:28.716 --> 00:36:30.126 A:middle
those six textures we saw

00:36:30.126 --> 00:36:32.116 A:middle
earlier on, if you aim for about

00:36:32.336 --> 00:36:35.606 A:middle
100k polygons, one set of 2k by

00:36:35.606 --> 00:36:38.136 A:middle
2k PBR textures and about ten

00:36:38.136 --> 00:36:39.956 A:middle
seconds of animation, this is

00:36:39.956 --> 00:36:40.916 A:middle
typically good for those

00:36:40.916 --> 00:36:42.216 A:middle
high-memory devices we mentioned

00:36:42.216 --> 00:36:42.576 A:middle
earlier on.

00:36:43.156 --> 00:36:45.976 A:middle
If in doubt, always test your

00:36:45.976 --> 00:36:47.786 A:middle
model on a device to make sure

00:36:47.786 --> 00:36:49.166 A:middle
that it renders and loads as you

00:36:49.946 --> 00:36:52.116 A:middle
would expect.

00:36:52.236 --> 00:36:53.736 A:middle
As you optimize your models for

00:36:53.796 --> 00:36:55.336 A:middle
use in AR Quick Look, a few

00:36:55.336 --> 00:36:56.906 A:middle
things to keep in mind.

00:36:57.636 --> 00:36:59.316 A:middle
Do be sure to freeze any

00:36:59.316 --> 00:37:00.656 A:middle
transforms in your models and


00:36:59.316 --> 00:37:00.656 A:middle
transforms in your models and

00:37:00.656 --> 00:37:01.956 A:middle
merge any adjacent vertices to

00:37:02.196 --> 00:37:03.576 A:middle
tidy them up ready for export.

00:37:04.496 --> 00:37:06.306 A:middle
And if you can, try and use a

00:37:06.306 --> 00:37:08.086 A:middle
single material and texture set

00:37:08.086 --> 00:37:08.976 A:middle
for the entire model.

00:37:10.056 --> 00:37:11.526 A:middle
This enables you to optimize how

00:37:11.526 --> 00:37:12.866 A:middle
you pack the different parts of

00:37:12.866 --> 00:37:14.456 A:middle
that model into those square

00:37:14.456 --> 00:37:15.396 A:middle
textures that you're using.

00:37:15.926 --> 00:37:18.666 A:middle
And if you don't need a texture,

00:37:19.256 --> 00:37:21.416 A:middle
don't include it.

00:37:21.416 --> 00:37:22.256 A:middle
If none of the parts of your

00:37:22.256 --> 00:37:23.266 A:middle
model are made from metal,

00:37:23.266 --> 00:37:24.336 A:middle
there's no need to provide a

00:37:24.336 --> 00:37:25.076 A:middle
metallic texture.

00:37:25.416 --> 00:37:26.866 A:middle
The default is non-metallic for

00:37:26.866 --> 00:37:28.306 A:middle
any model that's loaded.

00:37:29.316 --> 00:37:30.846 A:middle
When you're choosing where to

00:37:30.846 --> 00:37:32.116 A:middle
spend your texture budget,

00:37:32.616 --> 00:37:34.236 A:middle
prioritize the areas that give

00:37:34.236 --> 00:37:35.876 A:middle
most realism to that model.

00:37:35.876 --> 00:37:38.046 A:middle
For some models, that might be a

00:37:38.116 --> 00:37:39.646 A:middle
high-resolution albedo texture.

00:37:40.176 --> 00:37:41.116 A:middle
For others, it might be better

00:37:41.176 --> 00:37:42.886 A:middle
spent on roughness or the normal

00:37:42.886 --> 00:37:42.976 A:middle
map.

00:37:45.136 --> 00:37:46.636 A:middle
And remember the pixels actually

00:37:46.636 --> 00:37:48.486 A:middle
have a physical size in AR.

00:37:49.656 --> 00:37:50.856 A:middle
If you're printing a model of a

00:37:50.856 --> 00:37:52.206 A:middle
thimble, and it's one inch

00:37:52.256 --> 00:37:54.566 A:middle
across, there's probably no need

00:37:54.566 --> 00:37:56.376 A:middle
to use a 2k by 2k texture for

00:37:56.376 --> 00:37:56.443 A:middle
it.

00:37:56.786 --> 00:37:58.116 A:middle
Those pixels will be tiny in the

00:37:58.116 --> 00:37:59.186 A:middle
real world.


00:38:00.586 --> 00:38:02.156 A:middle
And although we want models to

00:38:02.156 --> 00:38:03.986 A:middle
look great, we also need to

00:38:03.986 --> 00:38:05.866 A:middle
balance texture size and quality

00:38:05.866 --> 00:38:06.846 A:middle
against file size.

00:38:07.466 --> 00:38:08.496 A:middle
If a model is being downloaded

00:38:08.496 --> 00:38:10.056 A:middle
from a website, we want it to be

00:38:10.056 --> 00:38:11.646 A:middle
a good size for downloading and

00:38:11.646 --> 00:38:13.376 A:middle
also for sharing via messages

00:38:13.376 --> 00:38:15.006 A:middle
and mail and other means.

00:38:17.156 --> 00:38:18.796 A:middle
So, with all of that in mind,

00:38:19.516 --> 00:38:20.416 A:middle
how do we make these things?

00:38:21.416 --> 00:38:23.276 A:middle
Well for this, we have a usdz

00:38:23.276 --> 00:38:24.026 A:middle
Converter.

00:38:25.286 --> 00:38:26.806 A:middle
This is a command line tool that

00:38:27.076 --> 00:38:28.976 A:middle
will convert existing 3D models

00:38:29.136 --> 00:38:30.286 A:middle
to usdz format.

00:38:31.486 --> 00:38:34.516 A:middle
It ships inside Xcode 10, and in

00:38:34.516 --> 00:38:36.556 A:middle
addition to creating usdz files,

00:38:37.206 --> 00:38:38.726 A:middle
you could also use it to map PBR

00:38:38.726 --> 00:38:40.646 A:middle
textures to the meshes and

00:38:40.646 --> 00:38:42.176 A:middle
submeshes inside those existing

00:38:42.176 --> 00:38:42.476 A:middle
models.

00:38:43.156 --> 00:38:47.226 A:middle
It's X3 input format, OBJ files,

00:38:47.446 --> 00:38:49.706 A:middle
Alembic files, and existing USD

00:38:49.706 --> 00:38:52.736 A:middle
files, either USDA or USDC, the

00:38:52.736 --> 00:38:54.586 A:middle
ASCII and binary versions of

00:38:55.106 --> 00:38:55.206 A:middle
USD.

00:38:56.496 --> 00:38:58.456 A:middle
Before we create one, let's take

00:38:58.456 --> 00:38:59.396 A:middle
a look at what it is we're going

00:38:59.396 --> 00:38:59.736 A:middle
to make.

00:38:59.876 --> 00:39:01.586 A:middle
Let's look inside a usdz file.


00:38:59.876 --> 00:39:01.586 A:middle
Let's look inside a usdz file.

00:39:03.036 --> 00:39:04.406 A:middle
In essence, these are

00:39:04.406 --> 00:39:06.146 A:middle
uncompressed zip archives.

00:39:06.926 --> 00:39:09.626 A:middle
The first file is always a usdc

00:39:09.756 --> 00:39:10.016 A:middle
file.

00:39:10.786 --> 00:39:12.236 A:middle
This contains the model's mesh,

00:39:12.546 --> 00:39:13.936 A:middle
its animation, if it has some,

00:39:13.936 --> 00:39:15.536 A:middle
and any material definitions it

00:39:15.536 --> 00:39:15.726 A:middle
needs.

00:39:16.976 --> 00:39:17.936 A:middle
And then, the remainder of the

00:39:17.936 --> 00:39:19.916 A:middle
files in the archive are any

00:39:19.996 --> 00:39:21.276 A:middle
textures, any images, like the

00:39:21.276 --> 00:39:22.876 A:middle
ones we saw earlier on.

00:39:24.116 --> 00:39:25.446 A:middle
If you're thinking of creating

00:39:25.446 --> 00:39:27.666 A:middle
your own tooling to build usdz

00:39:27.666 --> 00:39:29.406 A:middle
files, the great news is that

00:39:29.406 --> 00:39:30.246 A:middle
this is that this is an open

00:39:30.246 --> 00:39:32.436 A:middle
format and Pixar have published

00:39:32.486 --> 00:39:33.856 A:middle
the direct specification for

00:39:33.856 --> 00:39:36.536 A:middle
usdz on the graphics.pixar.com

00:39:37.106 --> 00:39:37.206 A:middle
site.

00:39:38.836 --> 00:39:40.446 A:middle
To create one with a usdz

00:39:40.446 --> 00:39:42.486 A:middle
converter, first note that we

00:39:42.486 --> 00:39:44.476 A:middle
call the tool with xcrun because

00:39:44.476 --> 00:39:45.556 A:middle
it shifts inside Xcode.

00:39:46.476 --> 00:39:47.516 A:middle
We pass in the name of the model

00:39:47.516 --> 00:39:49.436 A:middle
we want to convert, an OBJ file

00:39:49.436 --> 00:39:51.206 A:middle
in this case, and the file name

00:39:51.206 --> 00:39:52.866 A:middle
of the usdz we want to have the

00:39:52.866 --> 00:39:53.706 A:middle
other end.

00:39:54.676 --> 00:39:56.766 A:middle
To map PBR textures to the

00:39:56.766 --> 00:39:59.246 A:middle
meshes they're in, we use the -g

00:39:59.246 --> 00:40:00.816 A:middle
option, followed by the name of


00:39:59.246 --> 00:40:00.816 A:middle
option, followed by the name of

00:40:00.816 --> 00:40:02.216 A:middle
one of the groups, a mesh or a

00:40:02.216 --> 00:40:03.506 A:middle
submesh that we want to map them

00:40:03.506 --> 00:40:05.356 A:middle
to, and then we can provide any

00:40:05.356 --> 00:40:06.706 A:middle
number of these textures for

00:40:06.706 --> 00:40:07.456 A:middle
that particular group.

00:40:08.886 --> 00:40:10.326 A:middle
To map multiple textures to

00:40:10.326 --> 00:40:12.036 A:middle
multiple groups, we can use the

00:40:12.036 --> 00:40:13.586 A:middle
-g option multiple times, as

00:40:13.586 --> 00:40:15.126 A:middle
many as we need, to map all the

00:40:15.126 --> 00:40:15.886 A:middle
textures in our model.

00:40:16.426 --> 00:40:18.406 A:middle
And if you're not sure what the

00:40:18.406 --> 00:40:19.646 A:middle
